554
62:52.770 --> 63:00.110
in the four cases as follows; first, if X, Y equals zero, zero, then these are the probabilities

555
63:00.110 --> 63:10.260
of the various measurement outcomes, and you have to either think back or look back at the analysis
that we just went through to conclude that using our formula.

556
63:10.260 --> 63:16.770
Over here, we can see the
different state vectors drawn as they were before, and the color coding here
is that blue corresponds

557
63:16.770 --> 63:22.170
to the outcome zero and red
corresponds to the outcome one.

558
63:22.170 --> 63:28.380
You can see that the angle
between the blue vectors and the angle between the red
vectors is relatively small,

559
63:28.380 --> 63:36.600
it's pi over eight in both cases, so the cosine is relatively large, and that means that the
probability that the two outcomes

560
63:36.600 --> 63:40.710
are equal is relatively large.

561
63:40.710 --> 63:48.540
In the case that X, Y equals zero, one, it's a similar situation, the
angles between the vectors having the same color is small,

562
63:48.540 --> 63:54.210
so the probability of
equal outcomes is again, relatively large.

563
63:54.210 --> 64:02.290
The third case is similar, and in the fourth case
when X, Y equals one, one, something interesting happens,
this time, just by the way,

564
64:02.290 --> 64:08.910
these vectors have been chosen, we see that the angles between
vectors having the same color

565
64:08.910 --> 64:16.350
are relatively large, and specifically the angles are three times
pi over eight in both cases.

566
64:16.350 --> 64:24.510
This means that the probability
that the measurement outcomes is equal is relatively small, but this is the one case
in which Alice and Bob win

567
64:24.510 --> 64:28.590
when their answers disagree,
so it's what we want.

568
64:28.590 --> 64:36.295
Once again, here are the vectors: when X, Y equals zero, zero,
when Xx, Y equals zero, one,

569
64:36.295 --> 64:41.970
when X, Y equals one, zero,
and when X, Y equals one, one.

570
64:41.970 --> 64:48.000
And perhaps this geometric
picture is helpful in building some intuition
for how this strategy works

571
64:48.000 --> 64:53.310
and why these various angles were chosen in the way that they were.

572
64:53.310 --> 65:00.120
To finish off the lesson, I'll make a few brief
remarks about the CHSH game.

573
65:00.120 --> 65:05.490
First, as I've already mentioned, this example isn't always
described as a game.

574
65:05.490 --> 65:13.230
In the physics community, for instance, it's more common that
the example is described simply as an experiment rather than a game

575
65:13.230 --> 65:18.930
and Alice and Bob are
viewed as being detectors rather than players.

576
65:18.930 --> 65:26.970
The basic idea of an experiment like this where entanglement leads
to statistical results that are inconsistent with
any classical description

577
65:26.970 --> 65:34.890
or more generally any
theory based on so-called local hidden variables,
is due to John Bell, the namesake of the Bell states,

578
65:34.890 --> 65:40.440
and so people often refer
to experiments of this sort as Bell tests.

579
65:40.440 --> 65:47.040
Sometimes people also
refer to Bell's theorem, which can be formulated in different ways, but it basically says
that quantum mechanics

580
65:47.040 --> 65:51.780
is not compatible with so-called local hidden variable theories.

581
65:51.780 --> 65:58.110
The CHSH game or inequality is essentially a very nice and clean
example of a Bell test,

582
65:58.110 --> 66:05.190
and you can think about
this example as a proof or a demonstration of Bell's theorem.

583
66:05.190 --> 66:12.300
The second remark is that the CHSH game offers us one way to experimentally test that the theory of quantum information

584
66:12.300 --> 66:18.630
is an accurate theory. We can actually set up experiments that implement the CHSH game,

585
66:18.630 --> 66:26.040
including the sort of
strategy based on entanglement that I had just described, and
see if it works, and it does.

586
66:26.040 --> 66:34.080
This provides us with a
high degree of confidence that entanglement is real, and unlike the perhaps
vague or poetic ways

587
66:34.080 --> 66:40.860
that we try to come up with
to explain entanglement, the CHSH game or experiment
gives us a concrete

588
66:40.860 --> 66:43.980
and testable way to observe entanglement.

589
66:43.980 --> 66:51.780
If that sounds important,
it's because it is, and the 2022 Nobel Prize
in physics acknowledges exactly this.

590
66:51.780 --> 66:58.440
The prize was awarded to
Alain Aspect, John Clauser, who is the C in CHSH, and Anton Zeilinger

591
66:58.440 --> 67:07.747
for experiments with entangled photons that established the violation
of Bell inequalities, or in other words, that
showed that quantum strategies

592
67:07.747 --> 67:12.090
of the sort that I described actually work and outperform classical strategies.

593
67:12.090 --> 67:18.330
And if you're interested in
learning more about this, I encourage you to check out
the video on Bells Theorem by my colleague Olivia Lanes,

594
67:18.330 --> 67:22.529
right here on the Qiskit YouTube channel.

595
67:22.529 --> 67:29.730
And finally, the topic of
non-local games more generally is truly fascinating, and it's
an active area of research

596
67:29.730 --> 67:36.090
that brings together
physics, computer science, and pure mathematics and there are still many
interesting questions

597
67:36.090 --> 67:40.830
about non-local games that
remain unanswered to this day.

598
67:40.830 --> 67:47.670
And that is the end of lesson four, as well as the end of
unit one of the series on the Basics of Quantum Information.

599
67:47.670 --> 67:54.240
The first lesson explained
how quantum information works for single systems in isolation, and the second lesson explained
how quantum information

600
67:54.240 --> 68:00.774
works for multiple systems,
which pretty naturally emerges from how it works for single systems.

